snippet.textDisplay:
@ anyone that might know more than me:
Can we just isolate the virus from infected patients' blood? and then inject it into pretty much any mammal. Pigs, rabbits, mice and sheep are commonly used. Even though it's unlikely that a human virus would make the other mammals sick, they would still mount an immune response to the (foreign) protein capsule of the virus. Due to this response, within a few days, the mammals' blood will be teaming with antibodies against the antigens of the viral protein, which are then extracted and purified in a lab thus having a colony of living antibody factories.
OR
You could also isolate the activated B cells (called plasma cells) that are expressing antibodies from the people that already defeat the disease , and grow these cells in culture. Then you extract and purify the antibodies from the culture medium. Boom vaccine!
Although I don't know if we can have perpetual culturing from this cells but hey! that's an idea.

@ anyone that might know more than me:
Can we just isolate the virus from infected patients' blood? and then inject it into pretty much any mammal. Pigs, rabbits, mice and sheep are commonly used. Even though it's unlikely that a human virus would make the other mammals sick, they would still mount an immune response to the (foreign) protein capsule of the virus. Due to this response, within a few days, the mammals' blood will be teaming with antibodies against the antigens of the viral protein, which are then extracted and purified in a lab thus having a colony of living antibody factories. 
OR
You could also isolate the activated B cells (called plasma cells) that are expressing antibodies from the people that already defeat the disease , and grow these cells in culture. Then you extract and purify the antibodies from the culture medium. Boom vaccine! 
Although I don't know if we can have perpetual culturing from this cells but hey! that's an idea.
